		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    The Soloing Enchanter</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:lorelei38@hotmail.com">lorelei38</a> | 
		            4/7/2000 1:56:19 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Enchanters are my favorite class. Not only are they VERY fun, but if played right, VERY effective.<BR>
Soloing can be tricky though, because an Enchanter has low HP and the worst pet in the game.<BR>
<BR>
There are two strategies: One for One MOB and one for Multiple MOBs.<BR>
<BR>
One MOB: This is the shakiest strategy. Also known as the stun-n-pet technique. You spot a MOB in the distance. Hit it with a debuff or DOT first, and try to get more off as it comes for you. Let it hit you **ONCE** to get your useless pet into action. Then, don't mezmerize, stun. Stuns are wickedly effective, making it so that the MOB can't even hit. Root is also nice, but you or your pet can get hit. So stun instead. If stunned often, you and the pet should take little to no damage, and the MOB will be dropped.<BR>
<BR>
Multiple MOBs: You see three MOBs on the horizon. DOT or debuff one of them. That's the one you're gonna fight first, so remember it. I don't want you mezmerizing it and attacking one, just to have your DOT counteract the Mez. When they get close to you, you WILL be hit. But your pet will spring into action, allowing you to cast an Area-Effect stun. Then mezmerize the other two, and use the stun-n-pet technique mentioned. You can drop that one, then pick off the others using the same technique.<BR>
<BR>
Enchanters can do this at level 4, with Mesmerize and Color Flux.
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
